00:50:32.201 --> 00:50:37.310
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #6: I think Google
does a lot of this. We opt people into advertising

00:50:37.310 --> 00:50:44.870
on ad networks that they don't know about,
hopefully in their best interest. Privacy

00:50:44.870 --> 00:50:53.840
issues as well. How does paternalism and practical
wisdom help us walk that line in those areas

00:50:53.840 --> 00:50:54.840
particularly?

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:59.380
&gt;&gt;Barry Schwartz: This is an incredibly interesting
and complicated question. I'll give you a

00:50:59.380 --> 00:51:05.390
brief pass at it. Sunstein and Thaler, when
they wrote their book called "Nudge" were

00:51:05.390 --> 00:51:09.990
very insistent and I think it must be because
Thaler is an economist, that you don't nudge

00:51:09.990 --> 00:51:15.320
people in a direction because it's good for
society or even because it's good for them.

00:51:15.320 --> 00:51:21.650
You nudge them only when you have independent
evidence that it's what they want. So, if

00:51:21.650 --> 00:51:27.190
you didn't know that 96% of Americans approved
of organ donation, it'd be hard to justify

00:51:27.190 --> 00:51:33.720
moving to an opt-out system of organ donation.
That seems to me to be way too cautious.

00:51:33.720 --> 00:51:38.570
So, I think it's appropriate to nudge people
in directions that are good for them, whether

00:51:38.570 --> 00:51:44.480
they want it or not, or that are good for
society. The critical thing is that you are

00:51:44.480 --> 00:51:49.900
not forcing people. People can opt out. If
they don't opt out, what they end up getting

00:51:49.900 --> 00:51:54.320
and what they end up doing makes them better
off and all the rest of us better off.

00:51:54.320 --> 00:52:00.810
But what exactly is the level of privacy for
example, that's the right level of privacy

00:52:00.810 --> 00:52:06.600
to serve the interest of individuals and the
interest of the collective? That's a really,

00:52:06.600 --> 00:52:13.860
really hard question to answer. But I think
it's one that's worth asking because defaults

00:52:13.860 --> 00:52:20.290
have incredible, I mean, Facebook is a classic
example of the power of default. People didn't

00:52:20.290 --> 00:52:26.310
realize that they were parading all of their
weapons and their body parts for the entire

00:52:26.310 --> 00:52:31.820
world to see. They just thought that their
closest 12 to 15 thousand friends would know

00:52:31.820 --> 00:52:34.420
about their unusual habits and hobbies.

00:52:34.420 --> 00:52:38.740
It turns out no. Everybody, including anyone
who might employ them got to find out about

00:52:38.740 --> 00:52:43.640
that. It wasn't deliberate on the part of
the people who did this. It was the default.

00:52:43.640 --> 00:52:48.350
So, there are some defaults that are better
than others. And it takes a lot of work and

00:52:48.350 --> 00:52:51.830
understanding of people to figure out which
defaults are the right ones.

00:52:51.830 --> 00:52:59.210
The other thing I'll say is this. It is absolutely
crucial, in my mind, that Google's integrity

00:52:59.210 --> 00:53:06.610
be unimpeachable so that when people see the
ranking of hits when they type in a search

00:53:06.610 --> 00:53:14.600
term, they know that there is no pecuniary
interest driving that hierarchy. It is instead

00:53:14.600 --> 00:53:19.790
the result of a very smart algorithm that
will only get smarter and that is designed

00:53:19.790 --> 00:53:23.250
to serve what the client's needs are.

00:53:23.250 --> 00:53:31.380
That's a very precious resource to guard and
nurture, because once you lose that sense

00:53:31.380 --> 00:53:37.050
on the part of the public that you're in it
for the public's good, it'll take you a generation

00:53:37.050 --> 00:53:38.360
to recapture it.

00:53:38.360 --> 00:53:46.840
My own concern is that Google has gotten a
little bit careless about preserving the unimpeachability

00:53:46.840 --> 00:53:52.910
of its integrity in the service of a business
model that pushes, obviously pushes in a different

00:53:52.910 --> 00:53:56.290
direction. So, I don't think you can put a
price on that.

00:53:56.290 --> 00:54:01.030
I think its value is essentially infinite
and it is something that is really easy to

00:54:01.030 --> 00:54:04.670
lose and then hard to recapture. That help?

